        "title": "See also"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The standard deviation is the square root of the average of the squared\ndeviations from the mean: "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "std = sqrt(mean(abs(x - x.mean())**2))"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The average squared deviation is normally calculated as\n"
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "x.sum() / N"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ", where "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "N = len(x)"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ".  If, however, "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "ddof"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is\nspecified, the divisor "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "N - ddof"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is used instead. In standard\nstatistical practice, "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "ddof=1"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " provides an unbiased estimator of the\nvariance of the infinite population. "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "ddof=0"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " provides a maximum\nlikelihood estimate of the variance for normally distributed variables.\nThe standard deviation computed in this function is the square root of\nthe estimated variance, so even with "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "ddof=1"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ", it will not be an\nunbiased estimate of the standard deviation per se."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Note that, for complex numbers, "
              },
              {
                "external_url": "",
                "href": "/docs/api/ops/std",
                "kind": "link",
                "target": "std",
                "text": "std"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " takes the absolute value before\nsquaring, so that the result is always real and nonnegative."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "For floating-point input, the "
              },
              {
                "kind": "emphasis",
                "text": "std"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is computed using the same\nprecision the input has. Depending on the input data, this can cause\nthe results to be inaccurate, especially for float32 (see example\nbelow).  Specifying a higher-accuracy accumulator using the "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "dtype"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "\nkeyword can alleviate this issue."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Notes"
      },
